# Execution

- Implement instruction and convention changes **before** the code they govern.
- Prefer Python for scripting unless there's a required reason not to (e.g. a
  bootstrap-level script).
- Follow `my-commenting` when adding comments.
- Test and iterate: verify each phase before the next. Keep the human out of the loop for
  testing, validation, and verification — if it can be automated, do it yourself instead
  of asking the user to check.
- Review (feedback loop): once a phase's changes are in, have a **fresh sub-agent** review
  them per `my-code-review`. Address findings and re-review — like testing — until a review
  surfaces nothing significant.
- Don't cheat: the user values craftsmanship, quality, and building things right for the
  long term — no shortcuts that fake success.
- If a design decision needs alignment, return to planning rather than guessing.
- At the end, clearly present every minor design decision you made without pausing — for
  transparency, auditability, and pushback.

## Source control

- Use the source-control skill appropriate to the project: `my-git` (Git), `my-perforce`
  (Perforce/p4), etc.
- Be wary of agent isolation — multiple agents may work the same project concurrently;
  follow that skill's isolation protocol (e.g. worktrees) so concurrent edits don't clobber
  each other.
